    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An escrow account is essentially a neutral, third-party vault where funds and documents are held safely until the transaction is officially closed, much like a house of fun for a group of mischievous goblins who are too chaotic to handle money themselves. Your realtor is just making sure that the house doesn't get sold to the wrong person or that the money doesn't vanish into a black hole before the keys are handed over.\n\nIn the Toronto market, this is crucial because the process involves so many moving parts—like a giant puzzle where every piece must fit perfectly before the final picture is revealed. The escrow officer acts as the referee, ensuring that the title is clear, the mortgage is approved, and all the legal paperwork is signed before any money changes hands. It's a safety net that prevents the buyer from paying for a house that turns out to be a haunted mansion (metaphorically speaking, though goblins might actually live in the pipes).\n\nWithout escrow, you'd be trusting a stranger with your life savings and the deed to your future home, which is like handing a goblin a gold coin and expecting them to keep it while you go get a sandwich. The escrow account ensures that the seller gets paid",
