    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand your frustration, and I apologize for the goblin digression! You're absolutely right to focus on the financial mechanics, and I'll keep the goblins strictly to the metaphorical realm from now on.\n\nRegarding your question about who manages the escrow account: In a typical Toronto real estate transaction, the **real estate agent (your realtor or the seller's agent) does not manage the escrow account**. Instead, the funds and documents are held by a neutral third party known as an **Escrow Officer** or sometimes a **Title Company**.\n\nThis third party acts as the impartial referee. Their job is to ensure that all conditions of the contract are met before releasing money to the seller or the buyer. They hold the funds in a separate, regulated bank account (often called a \"trust account\") specifically for that transaction, ensuring the money is safe until the very last moment of the closing.\n\nTo clarify the money flow:\n1.  **Your Deposit:** When you make an offer, a portion of your down payment and closing costs goes into this escrow account.\n2.  **The Mortgage:** Your lender will also deposit their portion of the loan amount into this account.\n3.  **",
